# Transparent Web Proxy and HTTPS Filtering

## Objective

Deploy transparent HTTP and HTTPS web proxy on OPNsense using Squid and SquidGuard to intercept, inspect, and filter all client web traffic without requiring manual browser proxy configuration.

## Environment

- OPNsense LAN IP: 10.200.200.254
- LAN subnet: 10.200.200.0/24
- Windows 10 client: 10.200.200.20
- Squid HTTP port: 3128
- Squid HTTPS intercept port: 3129

## Configuration Summary

- Installed Squid Web Proxy plugin on OPNsense
- Enabled Transparent HTTP Proxy mode
- Enabled SSL Inspection (HTTPS interception / SSL bump)
- Created internal CA certificate named OPNsense-webca
- Exported and installed CA certificate into Windows Trusted Root Certification Authorities
- Configured NAT port forward rules: HTTP to 3128, HTTPS to 3129
- Added LAN firewall rules to block direct HTTP and HTTPS bypass traffic
- Added firewall rule to block QUIC (HTTP/3) on UDP port 443 to force TLS over TCP
- Installed and enabled SquidGuard ACL blacklists
- Enabled social networks category blocking

## Key File and Path Reference

| Item | Path |
|------|------|
| Squid configuration | /usr/local/etc/squid/squid.conf |
| Access log | /var/log/squid/access.log |
| Cache log | /var/log/squid/cache.log |
| CA certificate | /var/squid/ssl/ca.pem |
| SSL certificate database | /var/squid/ssl_crtd/ |
| Certificate generator binary | /usr/local/libexec/squid/security_file_certgen |

## Issues Encountered and Resolved

### Issue 1 — SSL Certificate Database Not Initialized

**Symptom:** Squid produced segmentation fault on restart and "exiting due to repeated, frequent failure" messages. No HTTPS traffic was intercepted.

**Root Cause:** The ssl_crtd certificate store directory existed but was never initialized. Squid generates SSL certificates on demand and cannot function without this database. The initialization command also requires the directory to be created manually first — it cannot create it on its own.

**Resolution:**

```bash
mkdir -p /var/squid/ssl_crtd
chown squid:squid /var/squid/ssl_crtd
chmod 700 /var/squid/ssl_crtd
/usr/local/libexec/squid/security_file_certgen -c -s /var/squid/ssl_crtd -M 4MB
chown -R squid:squid /var/squid/ssl_crtd
service squid restart
```

Note: The correct binary path on OPNsense is /usr/local/libexec/squid/ and the correct database path is /var/squid/ssl_crtd. Both differ from older documentation.

---

### Issue 2 — QUIC Block Rule Too Broad, Breaking DNS

**Symptom:** After adding a firewall rule to block QUIC traffic, all browsing from the Windows client stopped working entirely. Squid access log remained empty.

**Root Cause:** The QUIC block rule was configured with protocol UDP and no destination port restriction, which blocked all UDP traffic from the LAN including DNS queries on UDP port 53. Without DNS resolution, the browser could not initiate any connections.

**Resolution:** Updated the firewall rule to target UDP port 443 specifically.

Correct LAN firewall rule order:

| Order | Action | Protocol | Destination Port | Purpose |
|-------|--------|----------|-----------------|---------|
| 1 | Block | TCP/UDP | 80 | Block HTTP bypass |
| 2 | Block | UDP | 443 | Block QUIC only |
| 3 | Block | TCP/UDP | 443 | Block HTTPS bypass |
| 4 | Allow | any | any | Default LAN allow |

The Allow rule must always appear last. Any Allow rule above the Block rules will neutralize them.

