### Issue 3 — Windows Client Bypassing OPNsense via Secondary Network Adapter

**Symptom:** Squid access log remained completely empty even after fixing all other issues. tcpdump on the OPNsense LAN interface (em1) showed no HTTP or HTTPS traffic from the Windows client, only SSH session traffic.

**Root Cause:** The Windows 10 VM had two active network adapters:

- Ethernet 1 — VirtualBox NAT adapter, IP 10.0.2.15, gateway 10.0.2.2, with direct internet access
- Ethernet 2 — OPNsense LAN adapter, IP 10.200.200.20, gateway 10.200.200.254

Windows assigned lower metric (higher priority) to Ethernet 1, routing all browser traffic directly through the VirtualBox NAT adapter and bypassing OPNsense entirely. NAT redirect rules never fired because the traffic never arrived on em1.

This is a security control bypass via alternate path — a dual-homed host with an uncontrolled secondary internet route renders all firewall and proxy controls ineffective.

**Resolution:** Disabled the VirtualBox NAT adapter on the Windows VM in VirtualBox settings by changing Adapter 1 from NAT to Internal Network. This forced all traffic through OPNsense.

All client VMs in this lab must use a single network adapter connected to the OPNsense Internal Network. No secondary NAT adapters should remain active.

