## Known Limitations of Transparent HTTPS Filtering

Modern browsers and websites have introduced protections that limit the effectiveness of transparent SSL interception. The following table documents what works and what does not in current environments.

| Issue | Interceptable by Squid | Recommended Workaround |
|-------|----------------------|------------------------|
| QUIC / HTTP3 traffic | No — UDP-based, bypasses TCP Squid | Block UDP port 443 at firewall |
| HSTS preloading | Partial | Clear browser HSTS cache for testing |
| Certificate pinning (Facebook, Google) | No | DNS-based blocking via Unbound |
| TLS 1.3 Encrypted Client Hello | No | DNS-based blocking via Unbound |

For sites that cannot be intercepted through SSL bump, DNS-based blocking using OPNsense Unbound DNS overrides is the recommended alternative. This blocks at the resolution layer and is unaffected by transport-layer protections.

## Result

Transparent HTTP proxy and SSL inspection confirmed working. Client browser traffic is intercepted and logged by Squid. SquidGuard category filtering is active. Browser certificate chains show OPNsense-webca as the issuer for intercepted HTTPS connections.
